    # [Scene: Rooftop Garden | Night]
    hide maya_reyes
    hide eli_navarro
    hide asha_malik

    scene bg ch12_e67f19_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Upbeat folk rhythm layered with brass—festive and propulsive]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Laughter, plates clinking, the soft hiss of a grill]
    "The rooftop is a balm and a charge at once. Warm bulbs create pockets of intimacy in the cooling air. The smell of grilled fish mixes with basil and the ever-present salt. People move like currents: hugging, arguing, promising to show up at the first board meeting."
    "You feel lighter and more exhausted than in weeks. Your muscles loosen with relief; your mind snaps awake with the lines of obligations that will arrive like tide."
    "Rosa pulls you into a hug that smells like coffee and cardamom."
    show rosa_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "We will tell stories. We will keep your father's name on that board. We will plant. We will keep our market."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "Thank you, Rosa. For holding this town together."
    "She pats your back as if it is a child she has comforted before. You hear the deep, honest conversations spooling around you — neighbors comparing notes, twenty-year plans being sketched in the condensation on beer cans."
    "Eli appears with two paper cups of something too sweet but perfect. He hands you one and stands close enough that your shoulders brush."
    show eli_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "You did the heavy lifting in the room. I did the ceremonials with the clay."

    maya_reyes "You did more than the clay."

    eli_navarro "You make the plans feel like breathing."

    menu:
        "Take his arm and go greet the neighborhood leaders":
            "You loop your arm through his, letting the small, public intimacy be a shield. People see you together — not as a declaration but as a steadying force."
        "Stay where you are and listen to Rosa's stories":
            "You settle beside Rosa and let her stories wash over you. The weight of history fills your chest, both grounding and galvanizing."

    # --- merge ---
    "The rooftop's warm social energy carries on; connections are strengthened."
    "Conversations flare and return, the rooftop a microcosm of the long nights ahead. June moves through the clusters with economical efficiency; you catch her occasionally laughing at a neighbor's dry joke, glimpses of her humanity threading"
    "into the formal posture. Asha argues gently with a funder about the metrics the monitoring panel will use. Tomas jokes about repainting his shopfront in sea-glass green."
    "Eli catches your eye across the crowd and raises his cup. You lift yours in reply, clinking, tasting something like toasted sugar and the salt of the day. His thumb leaves a faint smudge of clay on your wrist; a small, tactile memory, oddly permanent."
    # [Scene: Tidal Steps | Late Night]
    hide rosa_alvarez
    hide maya_reyes
    hide eli_navarro

    scene bg ch12_e67f19_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, expansive piano with swelling strings — intimate and full]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Waves whispering, a distant foghorn like an old bell]
    "You and Eli walk down the tidal steps with the rest of the crowd thinning behind you. The basalt is cold and rough under your palm when you press your hand flat against it; the stone"
    "has the smell of algae and the taste of years. The night is both hollow with quiet and dense with possibility."
    "Your body hums with the aftershock of the day's decisions. Relief unspools into purpose: the clauses will need defending, panels will need members, funding streams will have to be tracked, living modules planted and watched. Guilt"
    "that had sat like a stone in your stomach slides, not gone but reshaped — now a tool."
    "Eli stands beside you and places his palm next to yours on the same basalt. His hand is warm; the broken clay from earlier has left an imprint you can still feel."
    show eli_navarro at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "We did it. It feels… strange. Like the first step on a rope bridge."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "A rope bridge that we'll be rebuilding as we cross. We'll tighten the knots as we go."
    "There is a fierceness to his smile that steadies something in you. He looks at the bay, at the lighthouse a thin promise on the horizon."

    maya_reyes "I carried so much guilt into that room. I thought I had to be perfect to protect everyone. But this—this is strategy. It's messy and legal and painfully real."

    eli_navarro "Perfect would have been hubris. This—' (he lifts his hand slightly) '—this is brave."
    "You let out a laugh that is half-exhale, half-sob. The arousal inside you has not settled; it has become a steady heat, an engine."
    "Asha's voice carries from the path behind you, small and clear."
    show asha_malik at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_malik "You made something that will demand every stubborn, terrible, beautiful hour of your life. And it will also give you the time to fight the right fights. That's balance."
    hide eli_navarro
    show rosa_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_alvarez "Make sure Tomas opens early Sunday — we'll swarm his shop on the first market day!"
    hide maya_reyes
    show tomas_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    tomas_reyes "Only if you all bring coffee!"
    "Laughter ripples down the steps like a lighter wave. The town's voices knit together — loud, human, imperfect and alive."
    "You feel Eli take your hand in his. It's not dramatic; it's practical and fierce and ordinary in the best way. You squeeze back."
    hide asha_malik
    show eli_navarro at center:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_navarro "We'll be tired. We'll fight. But we won't be alone."
    hide rosa_alvarez
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We won't be alone."
    "The lighthouse beam sweeps. The harbor holds. The agreement in your pocket is a patchwork cloth with the stitches still showing — not pretty, but strong where it matters. The town will have to show up."
    "You'll have to litigate. You'll have to plant and count and testify and sit through long, cold nights of minutes and memos. But the scaffolding is there: legal leverage, community oversight, funding for living shorelines, protections"
    "for small businesses, and a public structure that makes displacement more difficult."
    "Your guilt — that heavy, habit-forming thing — eases. It does not evaporate; it reshapes into resolve. You can feel the contours of what will be required: late nights in the lab and the rooftop, public"
    "hearings, the comfort of a shared tent of responsibility. Eli's presence beside you feels less like rescue and more like partnership."
